SIMPLE: starve
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Starve
<hw>Starve</hw> <pr>(st⟦aum⟧rv)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Starved</conjf>
<pr>(st⟦aum⟧rvd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Starving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sterven</ets> to die,
AS. <ets>steorfan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>sterven</ets>, G.
<ets>sterben</ets>, OHG. <ets>sterban</ets>, Icel. <ets>starf</ets>
labor, toil.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To die; to perish.</def>
<mark>[Obs., except in the sense of perishing with cold or
hunger.]</mark> <rj><au>Lydgate.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In hot coals he hath himself raked . . . ⟦br⟧
Thus <qex>starved</qex> this worthy mighty Hercules.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To perish with hunger; to suffer extreme hunger or
want; to be very indigent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sometimes virtue <qex>starves</qex>, while vice is fed.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To perish or die with cold.</def>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have I seen the naked <qex>starve</qex> for cold?</q>
<rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Starving</qex> with cold as well as hunger.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense, still common in England, but rarely used
in the United States.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Starve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Starve
<hw>Starve</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To destroy with
cold.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From beds of raging fire, to <qex>starve</qex> in ice⟦br⟧
Their soft ethereal warmth.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To kill with hunger; <as>as, maliciously to
<ex>starve</ex> a man is, in law, murder</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To distress or subdue by famine; <as>as, to
<ex>starve</ex> a garrison into a surrender</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Attalus endeavored to <qex>starve</qex> Italy by stopping their
convoy of provisions from Africa.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To destroy by want of any kind; <as>as, to
<ex>starve</ex> plants by depriving them of proper light and
air</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To deprive of force or vigor; to disable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pens of historians, writing thereof, seemed <qex>starved</qex>
for matter in an age so fruitful of memorable actions.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The powers of their minds are <qex>starved</qex> by disuse.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Starvedly</ent>⟦br⟧
